Chem. 10.1002/ange.201806729 Enzymology of Anthraquinone--Pyrone Ring Formation in  Complex Aromatic Polyketide Biosynthesis   Xian-Feng Hou, Yu-Jiao Song, Mei Zhang, Wenxian Lan, Song Meng, Chunxi Wang, Hai-Xue Pan,  Chunyang Cao,* and Gong-Li Tang*

Abstract:  Aromatic-fused -pyrones are structural features of many  bioactive natural products and valid scaffolds for medicinal chemistry.  However, the enzymology of their formation has not been completely  established. Herein, we demonstrate that TxnO9, a CalC-like protein  belonging  functions  as  an  unexpected  anthraquinone--pyrone  synthase  involved  in  the  biosynthesis  of  antitumor  antibiotic  trioxacarcin  A  (TXN-A).  Structural  analysis  by  NMR identified a likely substrate/product-binding mode and putative  key active sites of TxnO9, which guided us to propose an enzymatic  mechanism.  Moreover,  we  found  that  a  subset  of  uncharacterized  homologous  proteins  bearing  an  unexamined  Lys-Thr  dyad  exhibit  the  same  function.  Therefore,  the  functional  assignment  and  mechanistic  investigation  of  this  -pyrone  synthase  elucidated  an  undescribed  step  in  TXN-A  biosynthesis,  and  the  discovery  of  this  new  branch  of  polyketide  heterocyclases  expands  the  functions  of  the START superfamily.

-Pyrone  moiety  is  a  common  structural  unit  not  only  widely  spread  in  biologically  active  metabolites  but  also  considered as  a  privileged  scaffold  in  medicinal  chemistry  and  designed  libraries.[1]  Naturally  occurring  aromatic  ring-fused  -pyrone- containing  natural  products,  usually  derived  from  polyketides,  show various structural diversity and biological activities, thereby  exhibit  potency  for  use  in  pharmaceutical,  cosmetic,  and  food  industries.[1]  Among  the  benzoannelated  -pyrones  distributed  termed  as  chromes,  are  performed by two enzymatic steps for benzopyrone formation: a  chalcone  isomerase-mediated  heterocyclization  and  a  flavone  synthase-governed  oxidation  (Figure  1A).[2]  Additionally,  the  formation  of  (bis-)naphtho--pyrones  existed  fungal  kingdom, is usually catalyzed by polyketide synthase (PKS) and  (Figure  1B).[3]  More  complex  subsequent  dehydratase  polyketides  containing  an  anthraquinone--pyrone  framework,  exemplified  by  trioxacarcin  (TXN),  gutingimycin,  parimycin,  saliniquinones  and  hedamycin  (Figures  1C),  have  been  widely  discovered from bacteria; however, the enzymatic formation of - pyrone still remains obscure.  TXN  family  antibiotics  are  complex  polycyclic  polyketides  with extraordinary biological activity and have attracted particular  in  chemical  synthesis,  biosynthesis,  and  drug  attentions

Supporting information for this article is given via a link at the end of  the document.  development in recent years.[4,5] TXN-A (1, Figure 1C) is one of  the  most  potent  members  with  remarkable  anti-malarial,  anti- bacterial  and  anti-tumor  activities.[6]  Previously,  genetic  characterization  of  the  txn  gene  cluster  established  a  rough  biosynthetic  pathway.[5]  However,  many  proteins  with  unknown  functions encoded by the gene cluster need to be further defined  for  their  physiological  roles  in  TXN  biosynthesis.  Herein,  we  report the functional and mechanistic elucidation of a previously  uncharacterized  CalC-like  protein,  TxnO9,  which  catalyzes  the  heterocyclization (C-O bond formation) and dehydration to form  an  anthraquinopyrone.  This  finding  thereby  provides  a  new  insight  into  the  formation  of  -pyrones  in  complex  polyketide  biosynthesis in bacteria.

Figure  1.  Known  routes  to  bio-generate  aromatic  ring-fused  -pyrones.  (A) Flavone  formation  in  plants:  i,  chalcone  isomerase,  ii,  flavone  synthase.  (B) The biosynthetic pathway for nor-rubrofusarin in fungi: i, PKS, ii, dehydratase AurZ. (C) Selected anthraquinopyrone-containing natural products.  Trioxacarcin A (TXN-A, 1) TxnO9  displays  sequence  homology  (36%  identity,  E  value  of  6.0  ×  10-20)  to  CalC,  an  enediyne  “self-sacrifice”  resistance  protein,[7] it belongs to a widely distributed STeroidogenic Acute  Regulatory protein related lipid Transfer (START) superfamily.[8]  Resistance  experiment  ruled  out  the  possible  self-resistant  function  of  TxnO9  (Figure  S1).  Its  gene  replacement  mutant  strain  S.  bottropensis  TG5017  (∆txnO9,  Figure  S3)  completely  lost the ability  to produce TXN-A; meanwhile, a new metabolite  (4)  was  observed  and  gene  complementation  could  restored  TXN-A biosynthesis (Figure 2A-II,  III). However, compound 4 is  very unstable and easily changed into 4a by decarboxylation. By  carefully  evaluating  the  MS  and  NMR  spectra,  we  determined  the  structures  of  4  and  4a  (Figures  2B,  S4-S13  and Table  S4).  These evidences not only confirmed that txnO9 is necessary for  TXN-A  biosynthesis,  but  also  hinted  that  TxnO9  may  catalyze  some reactions with 4 as a substrate.

To  validate  the  hypothesis,  txnO9  gene  was  overexpressed  in  E.  coli  BL21  (DE3)  to  yield  an  N-terminal  His6-tagged  fusion  protein  (Figure  S2).  By  feeding  4  into  E.  coli  containing  txnO9  expression  plasmid  pTG5022,  we  observed  that  4  was  completely  converted  into  a  new  compound  5  (Figure  2A-VIII- VIV).  Subsequently  biochemical  assay  in  vitro  afforded  similar  results:  with  the  consumption  of  substrate  4,  product  5  was  formed  governed  by  TxnO9  independent  of  any  cofactors  (Figure  2A-IV).  However,  no  product  could  be detected  when  4  was replaced by 4a, suggesting the essential role of the carboxyl  group.  By  amplification  of  the  enzymatic  reaction,  5  was  accumulated  sufficiently  for  structural  elucidation  by  NMR,  MS  and  comparison  with  4,  resulting  in  an  anthraquinopyrone  structure (Figures 2B, S14-S17 and Table S4). Similar to 4, 5 is  not  stable  and  easily  changes  into  5a  through  spontaneous  decarboxylation  (Figures  2B,  S18-S22  and  Table  S5).  Collectively,  these  results  demonstrate  that  TxnO9  catalyzes  both  heterocyclization  and  dehydration  reactions  to  form  an  oxygen-containing heterocyclic anthraquinopyrone scaffold.

Next, we elucidated the solution structure of TxnO9 by NMR  experiments. This 154-amino acid protein consists of five regular  α-helices,  ten  loops  and  eight  anti-parallel  β-strands  (Figure  S23).  All  triangular  cone-shaped  hydrophobic cavity with a height of 39.5 Å, a width of 28.2 Å and  a diameter of 15 Å. Significantly, we found no proteins of similar  structure  with  RMSD  <  3.0  Å  based  on  the  results  from  Dali  searching. Despite belonging to the START superfamily, TxnO9  is  distinguished  from  other  members.  The  typical  START  proteins, such as MLN64 [pdb:1EM2], birch allergen protein Bet  v1 [pdb: 4BKC], and polyketide cyclase/aromatases exemplified  by TcmN,[9,10] consist of a seven--stranded core, two helices in  the  N-terminal  segment  and  a  long  helix  at  the  C-terminus  packing  tightly  against  the  sheet  to  form  an  interior  triangular  cone-shaped  pocket  ligands.  However,  the  C-terminal  long  helix  in  TxnO9  is  split  into  three  short α-helices. In addition, TxnO9 bears two sets of antiparallel  β-sheet;  while  in  WhiE,  CalC,  TcmN  and  MIN64_START,  only  one set of β-sheet exists (Figure S24).  Given  the  fact  that  both  4  and  5  are  liable  to  decarboxylate  affording  4a  and  5a,  we  switched  to  solve  the  structures  of  complex  with  them  as  substrate  and  product  mimics.  NMR  titration  experiment  revealed  that  only  minor  chemical  shift  changes were observed but the intensities of most cross-peaks  for  accommodating  different

became  weaker  (Figures  S25-S26),  which  showed  that  both  TxnO9-4a and TxnO9-5a complexes (Figures 3A-3B) exhibit an  overall  fold  very  similar  to  that  of  the  free  state.  In  both  complexes,  the  orientations  of  5a  and  4a  are  almost  identical;  which  mainly  interact  with  helices  α1,  α2,  α5,  anti-parallel  β1-  and  β8-strands.  The  conformations  of  the  aromatic  ring  of  4a  and 5a are stabilized and fixed by interactions with hydrophobic  residues  Phe25,  Phe107,  Val117,  Leu119  and  Leu147  (Figure  S27).  Significantly,  two  hydrogen  bonds  are  formed  between  Thr146 of TxnO9 and the carbonyl group at C-13 of 4a, as well  as one between side-chain of Glu145 and the hydroxyl group at  C-14 of 4a, with distances of 3.50 Å and 3.41 Å between them,  respectively  (Figure  3E).  These  measurements  suggested  that  Glu145  and  Thr146  may  take  part  in  the  catalytic  reaction.  In  addition, the NOEs observed between the 6-CH3 of 5a and Hβ of  TxnO9-Arg9, Lys10, or between 6-CH3 of 4a  and Hβ of TxnO9- Ser11  (Figure  S28)  suggest  that  fragment  R9K10S11  might  be  involved in identifying the carboxyl group of the substrate during  the reaction.

To  test  these  hypotheses,  we  constructed  structural  models  of the complexes with 4 and 5 in program XPLOR-NIH using the  same intermolecular NOEs as for the complexes with 4a and 5a  (Figures 3C-3D). As shown in Figure 3G, the negatively charged  carboxyl  group  at  C-18  of  4  was  anchored  by  the  positively  charged residue Lys10 via a salt-bridge, which is consistent with  the  fact  that  4a  is  not  a  recognizable  substrate.  Moreover,  the  hydroxyl  groups  at  C-14  position  of  4  and  5  form  hydrogen- bonds  with  the  side  chain  of  residue  Glu145  (Figures  3G-3H),  similar to those observed in structures of TxnO9-4a and TxnO9- 5a. It  is  consistent  with  the  results  of  NMR  titration  experiments,  in  which  these  residues  were  perturbed  when  the  substrate  was  added  to  the  protein  solution.  Additionally,  mutants  T146A  and  K10G  abolished  catalytic  activity  (Figure  2A-VI-VII),  which  further  supported  that  the  hydroxyl  group  of  Thr146  and  the  amino  group  of  Lys10  are  essential  for  catalytic  activity  and  mutants  E145G  and  K10Q  showed  decreased  activity  (Figures  S29-S30).  In  summary,  these  experiments  further  highlight  the  key roles of residues Thr146, Lys10 and Glu145 for the catalysis  of TxnO9.  these  results,  we  proposed  an  enzymatic  mechanism  (Figure  3I).  First,  substrate  4  is  anchored  by  Lys10  via  forming  a  salt  bridge  between  the  carboxyl  group  at  C-18  and  the  ammonium  ion  of  Lys10.  Second,  the  substrate-bound  complex causes residue Glu145 to approach the hydroxyl group  at  C-14  then  forms  a  hydrogen  bond,  which  further  prompts  Thr146  to  keep  close  to  the  carbonyl  group  at  C-13  and  activates  it  by  forming  a  hydrogen-bond  (Figures  3G  and  3l).  Third,  the  hydroxyl  group  at  C-8  of  4  attacks  the  activated  carbonyl  group  at  C-13  by  nucleophilic  addition  to  form  a  hemiketal  intermediate. Further, BLAST searches revealed that homologs of TxnO9  (E  value  between  6.0  ×  10-45  and  5.0  ×  10-108)  embedded  in  potentially  biosynthetic  gene  clusters  from  various  organisms  (Figure  S31);  however,  none  of  which  had  previously  been  functionally  annotated.  Multiple  sequence  alignment  revealed  a  subset  of  proteins  bearing  Lys10  and  Thr146  from  various  bacteria, as well as residues interacting with substrate are highly  conserved  (Figure  4A),  which  suggests  that  they  probably  play  the  same  roles  as  TxnO9.  Among  them,  only  the  hedamycin  biosynthetic  gene  cluster  has  been  generally  characterized.[11]  We  thereby  analyzed  this  hed  cluster  and  identified  that  HedB  contains  an  N-terminal  domain  homologous  to  TxnO9  (identity  64%) with conserved Lys10, Thr146, and hydrophobic substrate- binding residues (Figure 4A). Thus, we expressed and purified a  truncated  form  of  HedB  (TxnO9-like  domain,  Figure  S2)  for  biochemical  assay.  The  effective  conversion  of  4  into  5  (Figure  4B)  unambiguously  demonstrated  that  this  domain  exhibits  similar  function  to  TxnO9  in  hedamycin  biosynthesis.  Beyond  that,  we  further  expressed  three  proteins  WP_081958853.1  (identity  and  WP_083462199.1  (identity  69%)  from  Microtetraspora  glauca,

Thermomonospora  curvata,  and  Kitasatospora  griseola,  respectively  (Figure  S2),  to  test  their  functions  using  4  as  substrate. As expected, each of the three proteins exhibited the  same  function  as  TxnO9  to  catalyze  the  formation  of  5  (Figure  4B),  though  their  catalytic  efficiencies  were  different  (Figure  S32).  Like  TxnO9,  mutations  K10A  and  T146A  of  these  homologs  abolished  the  activity  (Figures  S33-S35).  These  collective  results  thereby  revealed  that  this  subfamily  catalyzes  heterocyclization-dehydration to form an anthraquinonepyrone.

Remarkably, two key residues (Lys10 and Thr146) identified  in  this  study  could  be  used  as  a  diagnostic  fingerprint  to  distinguish  potential  anthraquinopyrone  synthases  from  START  domain-containing  proteins.  This  superfamily  includes  a  large  set of uncharacterized proteins found in the Pfam database, and  the  number  will  no  doubt  continue  to  increase  with  the  rapid  accumulation of genomic sequence data. Compared to the well  studied  CalC-like  self-resistance  proteins[7]  and  polyketide  aromatases/cyclases,[10]  anthraquinopyrone  synthases  exhibit  a  totally different active sites and reaction mechanism, hereby are  defined  as  a  new  branch  (Figure  4C).  Because  polyketide  aromatases/cyclases have been considered as the fundamental  element to create diverse aromatic polyketide ring topologies,[12]  the anthraquinopyrone synthases thus provide a secondary tool  to  reshape  the  aromatic  anthraquinone  ring  system  by  fusing  a  six-membered  cyclic  unsaturated  ether. In  summary,  we  here  assigned  TxnO9  as  an  unexpected  anthraquinopyrone  synthase  involved  in  post-PKS  tailoring  process during TXN-A biosynthesis by a combination of genetic,  biochemical,  and  structural  characterization.  Beyond  the  known  plant benzopyrone (two-ring system) and fungal naphthopyrone  (three-ring  system)  structures  catalyzed  by  two  enzymes,  the  TxnO9-like  proteins  catalyze  both  heterocyclization  and  dehydration reactions to generate anthraquinopyrone, a four-ring  scaffold.  It  provides  another  route  for  pyrone  formation  in  complex  natural  product  biosynthesis  in  bacteria.  In  addition,  structural and enzymatic studies of TxnO9 provided new insights  into  the  heterocyclization  mechanism  of  anthraquinopyrone  synthase,  which  is  an  important  step  in  determining  the  complex  framework  anthraquinone--pyrone  polyketide antibiotics.
